WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.920 --> 00:00:08.060
Today we had ordinarily
expected Paulo Zanoni,

00:00:08.060 --> 00:00:12.780
who is a senior partner of
Goldman Sachs,

00:00:12.780 --> 00:00:17.184
to be with us,
and it turns out we are a lower

00:00:17.184 --> 00:00:23.048
priority than a new merger deal,
and we will have him a month

00:00:23.048 --> 00:00:28.015
from today,
which gives us time to pull

00:00:28.015 --> 00:00:36.538
together a bunch of important
details about the institutional

00:00:36.538 --> 00:00:42.991
foundations of capitalism,
and I'm going to use the term

00:00:42.991 --> 00:00:46.090
"wealth maximizing
law" today.

00:00:46.090 --> 00:00:51.490
If you think about what courts
do,

00:00:51.490 --> 00:00:55.633
and what legislators,
at any level from New Haven to

00:00:55.633 --> 00:00:58.640
the Congress of the United
States,

00:00:58.640 --> 00:01:04.954
they set rules which create
incentives and disincentives

00:01:04.954 --> 00:01:08.629
that affect how people behave.
 

00:01:08.629 --> 00:01:15.459
We're going to do four topics
today, but they're all ways of

00:01:15.459 --> 00:01:17.890
talking about that.
 

00:01:17.890 --> 00:01:20.667
I'm going to start with the
Coase Theorem,

00:01:20.667 --> 00:01:24.323
which is not in your reading
packet, and neither is it,

00:01:24.323 --> 00:01:26.560
strictly speaking,
a theorem.

00:01:26.560 --> 00:01:33.813
But it is a foundational set of
concepts that Hernando de Soto's

00:01:33.813 --> 00:01:38.650
book, which we are reading,
is built on.

00:01:38.650 --> 00:01:42.316
De Soto has,
in effect, taken the Coase

00:01:42.316 --> 00:01:47.816
Theorem, which is sixty years
back, and it won Ron Coase a

00:01:47.816 --> 00:01:51.580
Nobel Prize about thirty years
ago;

00:01:51.580 --> 00:01:57.226
has taken the Coase Theorem and
applied it to reality in a very

00:01:57.226 --> 00:01:58.410
lively way.
 

00:01:58.410 --> 00:02:02.230
The theorem is a good thing to
have in the background.

00:02:02.230 --> 00:02:05.783
Second, and very briefly,
we're going to look at a law

00:02:05.783 --> 00:02:07.484
case,
which is actually in the

00:02:07.484 --> 00:02:09.330
syllabus for a little later in
term,

00:02:09.330 --> 00:02:14.081
but I'm going to bring it
forward because this is really a

00:02:14.081 --> 00:02:16.750
good place to show its result.
 

00:02:16.750 --> 00:02:19.908
It's a case about whaling off
Cape Cod in the 1980s

00:02:19.908 --> 00:02:21.300
[correction: 1880s].
 

00:02:21.300 --> 00:02:25.215
And what's important about it
is not the facts of the case,

00:02:25.215 --> 00:02:28.318
but the way the judge reasoned
his decision.

00:02:28.318 --> 00:02:33.300
Third, we're going to do de
Soto in America,

00:02:33.300 --> 00:02:40.500
which was the assignment in
this book for today's class,

00:02:40.500 --> 00:02:43.491
and finally,
we're going to look at some of

00:02:43.491 --> 00:02:47.766
the finer grained distinctions
in the way you can structure a

00:02:47.766 --> 00:02:49.620
business organization.
 

00:02:49.620 --> 00:02:51.979
Coase Theorem.
 

00:02:51.979 --> 00:02:58.068
It's about this story,
this is a story we've all been

00:02:58.068 --> 00:03:00.060
through, right?
 

