00:05:43.779 --> 00:05:51.370
Prof: I think we're not
doing that one this afternoon.

00:05:51.370 --> 00:05:55.600
It's actually very suggestive,
right?

00:05:55.600 --> 00:05:59.779
That there is--that beneath
government,

00:05:59.779 --> 00:06:05.127
outside the actions of the
state, there is an enormously

00:06:05.127 --> 00:06:10.767
intricate system of informal
property which governs the way

00:06:10.767 --> 00:06:13.199
we actually function.
 

00:06:13.199 --> 00:06:18.649
That system of property can be
good,

00:06:18.649 --> 00:06:20.990
bad, or indifferent,
it can be just or unjust,

00:06:20.990 --> 00:06:27.079
it can be notoriously
inefficient, and in fact,

00:06:27.079 --> 00:06:32.120
if you think about the failure
of socialist regimes,

00:06:32.120 --> 00:06:37.512
one important explanation is
that the underlying informal

00:06:37.512 --> 00:06:43.098
norms about what people do with
their work lives were never

00:06:43.098 --> 00:06:49.069
integrated with the planned
economies in an effective way.

00:06:49.069 --> 00:06:55.040
Now--so that's something about
formality and informality.

00:06:55.040 --> 00:07:01.857
I also have here a watch,
