00:07:57.084 --> 00:07:58.019
less than $20?
 

00:07:58.019 --> 00:08:01.639
Student:  I think you're
a pretty trustworthy guy.

00:08:01.639 --> 00:08:06.526
Prof: Remember what I'm
trying to demonstrate is

00:08:06.526 --> 00:08:08.699
information asymmetry.
 

00:08:08.699 --> 00:08:16.384
This watch is worth about $8,
and it's a--and if I sold it to

00:08:16.384 --> 00:08:23.942
you what I would be doing is
stealing from the manufacturer,

00:08:23.942 --> 00:08:26.889
stealing the brand.
 

00:08:26.889 --> 00:08:32.128
One of the curious things about
watches these days--by the way,

00:08:32.128 --> 00:08:33.480
it works fine.
 

00:08:33.480 --> 00:08:36.879
Somebody gave it to me for my
birthday as a joke,

00:08:36.879 --> 00:08:42.320
it keeps, as far as I can tell,
perfect time,

00:08:42.320 --> 00:08:44.759
possibly better time than a
real Movado,

00:08:44.759 --> 00:08:48.870
and there's an interesting
problem about watches,

00:08:48.870 --> 00:08:49.830
right?
 

00:08:49.830 --> 00:08:56.581
Which is better,
a $9 Casio, the cheapest

00:08:56.581 --> 00:09:05.522
imaginable Casio or Timex;
or a Rolex, if the question is

00:09:05.522 --> 00:09:08.190
keeping good time?
 

00:09:08.190 --> 00:09:10.779
Student:  The Casio.
 

00:09:10.779 --> 00:09:11.320
Prof: Pardon?
 

00:09:11.320 --> 00:09:12.820
Student:  Probably the
Casio.

00:09:12.820 --> 00:09:15.256
Prof: Yeah,
the Rolex is a mechanical

00:09:15.256 --> 00:09:18.375
movement of brilliantly designed
and executed mechanical

00:09:18.375 --> 00:09:21.995
movement,
and it's not as good as an

00:09:21.995 --> 00:09:27.577
ordinary electronic watch;
doesn't keep time as well,

00:09:27.577 --> 00:09:33.486
and yet people are willing to
pay thousand to one multiples

00:09:33.486 --> 00:09:37.460
for the social meaning of the
brand.

00:09:37.460 --> 00:09:43.865
That means that there's an
enormous market for cheaply made

00:09:43.865 --> 00:09:46.676
watches,
gray market watches,

00:09:46.676 --> 00:09:52.557
or even black market watches,
which knock off a brand name

00:09:52.557 --> 00:09:59.735
and which people sometimes buy
really thinking that it's the

00:09:59.735 --> 00:10:02.897
real deal,
but more often,

00:10:02.897 --> 00:10:09.019
just thinking it's kind of fun
to buy an expensive brand for,

00:10:09.019 --> 00:10:10.570
say, $20.
 

00:10:10.570 --> 00:10:21.730
Well the Coase Theorem is about
those issues plus the one where

00:10:21.730 --> 00:10:25.509
this girl is vexed.
 

00:10:25.509 --> 00:10:31.176
And the one where she's vexed
is that the property rights to

00:10:31.176 --> 00:10:34.250
that toy are unclearly marked.
 

00:10:34.250 --> 00:10:41.115
I have a granddaughter who got
the boss gene from her mother

00:10:41.115 --> 00:10:45.995
and she's a first--
kindergartner and her first day

00:10:45.995 --> 00:10:49.932
at school they got out--
they brought out little plastic

00:10:49.932 --> 00:10:53.750
ants for the children to learn
basic arithmetic with and they

00:10:53.750 --> 00:10:57.485
put a pile of them on the--
in the middle of each table,

00:10:57.485 --> 00:10:58.788
and than four kids.
 

00:10:58.788 --> 00:11:05.523
And my granddaughter came home
complaining that the other kids

00:11:05.523 --> 00:11:07.509
had been to her.
 

00:11:07.509 --> 00:11:11.700
So her mother talked to the
teacher the next day,

00:11:11.700 --> 00:11:17.655
and the story was that our
grandchild had taken all the

00:11:17.655 --> 00:11:24.605
ants and put them in a pile and
then begun negotiating bilateral

00:11:24.605 --> 00:11:30.120
agreements to give some to the
other students.

00:11:30.120 --> 00:11:32.450
They didn't like that.
 

00:11:32.450 --> 00:11:40.663
Well, the Coase Theorem boiled
down is that if you have three

00:11:40.663 --> 00:11:45.517
conditions,
clear initial entitlements to

00:11:45.517 --> 00:11:51.089
property and this is what's
stressed most in the de Soto

00:11:51.089 --> 00:11:54.389
book;
clear entitlements to property;

00:11:54.389 --> 00:12:01.565
a high degree of transparency,
which is what's missing in the

00:12:01.565 --> 00:12:05.990
story about the bogus Movado
watch;

00:12:05.990 --> 00:12:13.528
and low transaction costs.
 

00:12:13.528 --> 00:12:17.320
The Nobel Prize in Economics,
announced today--

00:12:17.320 --> 00:12:23.504
they announced two of them,
but one of them went to Ollie

00:12:23.504 --> 00:12:26.912
Williamson,
formerly a colleague of ours

00:12:26.912 --> 00:12:31.149
here at Yale,
for inventing and elaborating

00:12:31.149 --> 00:12:35.620
the idea of transaction cost
economics.

00:12:35.620 --> 00:12:40.010
By trans--have we talked a
little about transaction costs

00:12:40.010 --> 00:12:40.558
here?
 

00:12:40.558 --> 00:12:45.879
About how hard it is to do--to
get a deal made?

00:12:45.879 --> 00:12:51.187
You know what deal you want to
make, but the--all the red tape

00:12:51.187 --> 00:12:56.408
that gets in the way makes it
very difficult to get there.

00:12:56.408 --> 00:13:05.269
Coase's principal point is that
in that tiny segment in the

00:13:05.269 --> 00:13:13.270
middle of the Ven diagram,
where these three conditions

00:13:13.270 --> 00:13:16.913
all obtain,
we should expect people to

00:13:16.913 --> 00:13:21.260
reach efficient allocations of
property no matter what the

00:13:21.260 --> 00:13:22.940
initial allocation.
 

00:13:22.940 --> 00:13:26.808
Now notice I didn't say,
and he doesn't say,

00:13:26.808 --> 00:13:30.678
fair or just allocations,
just efficient.

00:13:30.678 --> 00:13:36.524
And efficient in the sense that
people will trade to a point

00:13:36.524 --> 00:13:41.178
where there are no further
opportunities to--

00:13:41.178 --> 00:13:45.114
for mutual gain,
and you get to a so called

00:13:45.114 --> 00:13:49.330
Pareto efficient or contract
curve outcome.

00:13:49.330 --> 00:13:54.032
And I'm going to--I don't do
this to you very often,

00:13:54.032 --> 00:13:59.379
but we're going to do this with
a graphic demonstration.

00:13:59.379 --> 00:14:01.399
This is an Edgeworth box.
 

00:14:01.399 --> 00:14:06.345
I used one once before--does
anybody have any trouble about

00:14:06.345 --> 00:14:09.159
how an Edgeworth box is set up?
 

00:14:09.159 --> 00:14:11.379
Hum if you are.
 

00:14:11.379 --> 00:14:15.840
Okay, so Smith is here,
Voltaire is there.

00:14:15.840 --> 00:14:20.581
Smith gets that much paper and
that quantity of pens,

00:14:20.581 --> 00:14:24.139
Voltaire gets the obverse
quantities.

00:14:24.139 --> 00:14:28.577
If we start at the red dot,
Voltaire's entitlements are

00:14:28.577 --> 00:14:33.178
shown by the blue lines and
Smith's by the pink lines.

00:14:33.178 --> 00:14:40.153
Voltaire would prefer
anything--any outcome beyond

00:14:40.153 --> 00:14:46.129
this indifference curve going
this way,

00:14:46.129 --> 00:14:53.390
away from his point of origin,
and Smith would prefer anything

00:14:53.390 --> 00:14:58.629
that way from the pink
indifference curve.

00:14:58.629 --> 00:15:04.522
So there is a set of outcomes
which are clearly superior to

00:15:04.522 --> 00:15:10.413
the starting point and they're
in that set, that lozenge in

00:15:10.413 --> 00:15:11.428
shape.
 

00:15:11.428 --> 00:15:15.793
And so they will trade to that,
and if we just set it up as

00:15:15.793 --> 00:15:20.234
this is a rank order account of
what Smith wants and of what

00:15:20.234 --> 00:15:26.556
Voltaire wants,
S is that set of outcomes and

00:15:26.556 --> 00:15:30.370
those two--
S in the two diagrams is the

00:15:30.370 --> 00:15:31.149
same thing.
 

00:15:31.149 --> 00:15:35.428
Ultimately they'll get to an
outcome where the indifference

00:15:35.428 --> 00:15:38.379
curves are at tangency to one
another;

00:15:38.379 --> 00:15:41.690
there's no further gain from
trade,

00:15:41.690 --> 00:15:47.316
and there will be a whole set
of outcomes that fit that

00:15:47.316 --> 00:15:52.548
description,
forming the contract curve,

00:15:52.548 --> 00:15:57.975
all those points,
and the contract curve will be

00:15:57.975 --> 00:16:03.666
equivalent to this possibility
frontier in the other style of

00:16:03.666 --> 00:16:04.710
diagram.
 

00:16:04.710 --> 00:16:13.600
The--it's a really simple idea.
 

00:16:13.600 --> 00:16:18.409
The way to use the Coase
Theorem though is backward.

00:16:18.409 --> 00:16:20.649
The Coase Theorem is boring.
 

00:16:20.649 --> 00:16:25.090
Incidentally,
I was talking to my TA's this

00:16:25.090 --> 00:16:31.432
morning about the first round of
memos, and they had only one

00:16:31.432 --> 00:16:35.980
complaint: that they were often
boring.

00:16:35.980 --> 00:16:41.181
Not bad, but there was none of
the author's personality in most

00:16:41.181 --> 00:16:42.019
of them.
 

00:16:42.019 --> 00:16:48.326
You've all learned long since
how to write papers in college

00:16:48.326 --> 00:16:52.707
and get good grades,
but you ought to just

00:16:52.707 --> 00:16:56.769
occasionally put yourself into
it.

00:16:56.769 --> 00:17:03.028
Don't do it the standard way,
just go out on a limb.

00:17:03.028 --> 00:17:06.915
Now that's especially true if
you don't think you need to go

00:17:06.915 --> 00:17:09.420
to law school,
med school or an MBA.

00:17:09.420 --> 00:17:15.951
It's actually--I remember
making all the exact same

00:17:15.951 --> 00:17:21.308
calculations when I was where
you are,

00:17:21.308 --> 00:17:26.849
but a little risk taking in
writing actually endears you to

00:17:26.849 --> 00:17:34.430
those who read the work,
and often actually pays off.

00:17:34.430 --> 00:17:38.367
An interesting thing about
writing: After your B.A.,

00:17:38.367 --> 00:17:43.078
taking risks with your writing
turns out to be the only way of

00:17:43.078 --> 00:17:44.470
getting ahead.
 

00:17:44.470 --> 00:17:49.750
Standard issue writing pays up
to the B.A., and by and large

